### Berserk
A berserk creature is driven mad with blind rage, most commonly due to the effects of a drug, a curse, or a creature associated with madness. Many things may cause a creature to become berserk, but it is always specified by the feature.
#### Effects
A creature's mind is completely maddened after going berserk, making them gain the following while under the condition:
- The berserk creature must use its action each round to attack the creature nearest to it. If it can make extra attacks as part of the Attack action, it uses those extra attacks, moving to attack the next nearest creature after it fells its current target. If it has multiple possible targets, it attacks one at random.
- If it can use its reaction and/or bonus action to deal damage directly to a creature, it must do so.
- When a non-hostile creature moves out of a berserk creature's reach, it provokes an opportunity attack.
- It has disadvantage on Wisdom ability checks and saving throws and automatically fails Intelligence ability checks and saving throws.
- It can't cast or concentrate on spells.
- It is immune to the charmed and frightened conditions.
#### Removal
- The condition ends if the berserk creature starts its turn with no creatures within 60 feet of it that it can see or hear.
- A *calm emotions* spell, or any other feature that suppresses or removes the charmed condition, likewise affects a berserk creature.
#### Resistances and Vulnerabilities
- Creatures that have advantage against the charmed condition or have resistance to psychic damage have advantage against the berserk condition.
- Creatures that are immune to psychic damage or the charmed condition are also immune to the berserk condition.

